<p>A corporeal Patronus was one that was fully-formed, taking the shape of =
a bright, silvery, translucent animal. It was the strongest form a Patronus=
 could take, being able to fully drive Dementors away.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-P=
M_4-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/=
Patronus_Charm#cite_note-PM-4" aria-label=3D"Reference 4"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The animal species it took the form of was the one which the caster =
had the greatest affinity for. Furthermore, the specific animal forms that =
a corporeal Patronus took would vary from person to person and reflect each=
 individual's innermost personality. No two Patronuses were the same. Most =
Patronuses took the form of a mundane animal. <a href=3D"https://harrypotte=
r.fandom.com/wiki/Hedley_Fleetwood" title=3D"Hedley Fleetwood">Hedley Fleet=
wood</a>'s <a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Woolly_mammoth" t=
itle=3D"Woolly mammoth">woolly mammoth</a> Patronus was a notable exception=
. It was very rare for Patronuses to take the form of extinct animals. Patr=
onuses resembling a magical creature, such as <a href=3D"https://harrypotte=
r.fandom.com/wiki/Albus_Dumbledore" title=3D"Albus Dumbledore">Albus Dumble=
dore</a>'s <a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Phoenix" title=3D=
"Phoenix">phoenix</a> Patronus, were the most uncommon kind of all.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-WB_7-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fan=
dom.com/wiki/Patronus_Charm#cite_note-WB-7" aria-label=3D"Reference 7"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-PM_4-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://h=
arrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Patronus_Charm#cite_note-PM-4" aria-label=3D"Ref=
erence 4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Andros_=
the_Invincible" title=3D"Andros the Invincible">Andros the Invincible</a> w=
as the only known wizard capable of casting a Patronus the size of a <a hre=
f=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Giant" title=3D"Giant">giant</a>,<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-COSG_8-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://harrypo=
tter.fandom.com/wiki/Patronus_Charm#cite_note-COSG-8" aria-label=3D"Referen=
ce 8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> although whether it was a true giant or not is unknown.
</p><p>No reliable system for predicting the form of an individual's Patron=
us has ever been found.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-PM_4-18" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Patronus_Charm#cite_note-PM-4" =
aria-label=3D"Reference 4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>It should be noted that the animal was a reflection of the caster, n=
ot a reflection of the strength of the spell. While a rare and magical Patr=
onus undoubtedly reflected an unusual personality, it did not follow that i=
t was more powerful, or will enjoy greater success at defending its caster.=
 In fact, one of the most famous Patronuses of all time was a lowly <a href=
=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Mouse" title=3D"Mouse">mouse</a>, w=
hich belonged to a legendary young wizard called <a href=3D"https://harrypo=
tter.fandom.com/wiki/Illyius" title=3D"Illyius">Illyius</a>, who used it to=
 single-handedly hold off an attack from an army of Dementors, led by <a hr=
ef=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Raczidian" title=3D"Raczidian">Ra=
czidian</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-PM_4-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Patronus_Charm#cite_note-PM-4" aria-label=
=3D"Reference 4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Additionally, Patronus forms were subject to change if the caster we=
nt through an emotional upheaval of some sort, including falling in eternal=
, unchanging <a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Love" title=3D"=
Love">love</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Patronus_Charm#cite_note-39" aria-label=3D"R=
eference 39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> For example, <a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom=
.com/wiki/Nymphadora_Tonks" title=3D"Nymphadora Tonks">Nymphadora Tonks</a>=
's Patronus changed from its previous jack rabbit form to an ambiguous four=
-legged creature, which others guessed was a <a href=3D"https://harrypotter=
.fandom.com/wiki/Wolf" title=3D"Wolf">wolf</a> because it would reflect her=
 love for <a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Remus_Lupin" title=
=3D"Remus Lupin">Remus Lupin</a>, himself a werewolf.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-PM=
_4-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/P=
atronus_Charm#cite_note-PM-4" aria-label=3D"Reference 4"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Another=
 example was Severus Snape, whose Patronus was that of a doe, the same as <=
a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Lily_Potter_(I)" title=3D"Lil=
y Potter (I)">Lily Evans</a>, though this may have been the case all along =
rather than a change from its original form, as Snape was in love with Lily=
 for most of his life.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-DH33_19-2" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Patronus_Charm#cite_note-DH33-=
19" aria-label=3D"Reference 19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Based on the fact that Patronuses were conjured by recalling happy m=
emories, it stands to reason that a Patronus might change its form after on=
e fell in love and the memories used to conjure the Patronus largely revolv=
ed around the person the caster was in love with. In addition, it seemed th=
at some couples had "<i>complementary</i>" Patronuses (male and female form=
s of the same animal), such as Lily and <a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fand=
om.com/wiki/James_Potter_(I)" title=3D"James Potter (I)">James Potter</a>. =
It is, however, unknown if this was a coincidence or not.
</p><p>If a wizard was an <a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/An=
imagus" title=3D"Animagus">Animagus</a> and could summon a corporeal Patron=
us, their animal transformation and the Patronus animal might take the same=
 form. This was the case for <a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki=
/Minerva_McGonagall" title=3D"Minerva McGonagall">Minerva McGonagall</a> (a=
 <a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Cat" title=3D"Cat">cat</a>)=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-DH30_31-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://harry=
potter.fandom.com/wiki/Patronus_Charm#cite_note-DH30-31" aria-label=3D"Refe=
rence 31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> and James Potter (a <a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fa=
ndom.com/wiki/Deer" title=3D"Deer">stag</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-accio-quot=
e_34-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/=
Patronus_Charm#cite_note-accio-quote-34" aria-label=3D"Reference 34"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> Apparently, the form one's Patronus took may have been predetermined =
by the same inner-traits as the Animagus form.
</p><p>Remus Lupin's Patronus took the form of a true <a href=3D"https://ha=
rrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Wolf" title=3D"Wolf">wolf</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-pmlupin_40-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.co=
m/wiki/Patronus_Charm#cite_note-pmlupin-40" aria-label=3D"Reference 40"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"incontent_leaderboard fandom-ad-wrapper"><fandom-ad id=3D"inc=
ontent_leaderboard_8"></fandom-ad></div><h3><span class=3D"mw-headline" id=
=3D"Uses">Uses</span><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">[</span><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></h3>
<div class=3D"quote">
<dl><dd><span title=3D"Source:&nbsp;Pottermore">"<i>As a pure, protective m=
agical concentration of happiness and hope (the recollection of a single ta=
lisman memory is essential in its creation) it is the only spell effective =
against Dementors.</i>"</span></dd>
<dd>=E2=80=94 The Patronus is the only known method of defence against a De=
mentor<sup class=3D"noprint"><a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki=
/Pottermore" title=3D"Pottermore">[src]</a></sup></dd>
<dd></dd></dl></div>
<p>There were two known uses for the Patronus Charm. The first and main use=
 of the Patronus was to drive off certain <a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fa=
ndom.com/wiki/Dark_Arts" title=3D"Dark Arts">dark</a> creatures, such as <a=
 href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Dementor" title=3D"Dementor">D=
ementors</a> and <a href=3D"https://harrypotter.fandom.com/wiki/Lethifold" =
title=3D"Lethifold">Lethifolds</a>, and was the only known charm that would=
 work against them. As Dementors fed on happy memories, causing humans to d=
rown in their own sadness and hopelessness, the Patronus acted as a shield =
of sorts, of which the Dementor would try to feed off of instead =E2=80=94 =
and since the Patronus was comprised exclusively of positive feelings and c=
ouldn't comprehend negative emotion, the Dementor's influence couldn't affe=
ct it.
</p>
<figure class=3D"thumb mw-halign-left show-info-icon" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thu=
mb" style=3D"width: 250px"> 	<a href=3D"https://static.wikia.nocookie.net/h=
arrypotter/images/3/36/HarryPotterDeath_feature.jpg/revision/latest?cb=3D20=
111112202049" class=3D"mw-file-description image" style=3D"display: inline-=
